## What happened

Apple removed DSA from its native security frameworks (Security.framework / CryptoKit). On macOS, .NET's `DSA.Create()` delegates to Apple's crypto libraries, so it now throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`**. Linux (OpenSSL) and Windows (CNG) still have DSA support, which is why only macOS breaks.

This was flagged as a breaking change in the .NET 7+ era and has been progressively enforced. Your .NET 10 builds may have been working via a compatibility shim or were simply not exercising that code path on macOS CI.

## How to fix it

Since you only need to **verify** legacy signatures, replace the built-in `DSA` class with a managed (portable) implementation. **BouncyCastle** is the standard choice:

```bash
dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography
```

Then swap the verification logic:

```csharp
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Security;

public static bool VerifyDsaSignature(byte[] data, byte[] signature, DSAParameters dsaParams)
{
    // Convert .NET DSAParameters → BouncyCastle key
    var p = new Org.BouncyCastle.Math.BigInteger(1, dsaParams.P);
    var q = new Org.BouncyCastle.Math.BigInteger(1, dsaParams.Q);
    var g = new Org.BouncyCastle.Math.BigInteger(1, dsaParams.G);
    var y = new Org.BouncyCastle.Math.BigInteger(1, dsaParams.Y);

    var pubKey = new DsaPublicKeyParameters(y, new DsaParameters(p, q, g));

    var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA-1withDSA"); // match your original hash
    verifier.Init(false, pubKey);
    verifier.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
    return verifier.VerifySignature(signature);
}
```

This is a pure managed implementation — it works identically on Linux, Windows, and macOS with no native dependency.
